The microstructure and strength of concrete will be significantly impacted by an increase in the maximum size of particles used in a concrete mixture. Among the primary outcomes are: Microstructure: As aggregate sizes are increased, fewer aggregate particles will be present in a given volume of concrete. Less vacancies and more big aggregate particles will be evident as a consequence of a coarser microstructure. Porosity: Porosity will decrease when aggregate size is increased to its maximum. This is because bigger aggregate particles need less water to fill the spaces between them since they have a lower surface area than smaller aggregate particles. Compressive strength: As aggregates' maximum sizes grow, their compressive strength will as well. This is due to the fact that the concrete will be stronger since bigger aggregate particles can withstand compressive pressures better than smaller ones. Flexural strength: As aggregates' maximum sizes grow, flexural strength will also decrease. Larger aggregate particles are less able to sustain the tensile stresses that arise in concrete during bending because they are more fragile than smaller aggregate particles. Thermal conductivity: The maximum aggregate size will boost the concrete's thermal conductivity. This is due to the fact that larger aggregate particles will transmit heat more quickly than smaller ones since they have a greater thermal conductivity. Shrinkage: An increase in the maximum aggregate size will cause concrete to shrink more. This is due to the fact that larger aggregate particles need less water to fill the spaces between them since they have a lower surface area than smaller aggregate particles. This causes the water to cement ratio to drop and shrinkage to rise. In conclusion, increasing the maximum size of aggregates in a concrete mix will result in a coarser microstructure, less porosity, more big aggregate particles visible, a loss in flexural strength, an increase in compressive strength, a decrease in thermal conductivity, and greater shrinkage. It's vital to remember that the kind and characteristics of the aggregates being used, as well as the particular mix design, have a significant impact on the maximum size of aggregate's impact on the strength and microstructure of concrete. For instance, despite having bigger aggregate particles, the total strength may decrease if the aggregate is weaker than the cement paste. Therefore, while choosing the maximum size of aggregate to be used in a concrete mixture, it is crucial to carefully analyze the qualities of the aggregates and the particular needs of the project. 